I disagree on the first point.  There are many different professions that
work freelance out of a home-office, like illustrators or consultants.  As
someone else pointed out, most professionals will be honest about how many
hours they work.  

Speaking as a freelance illustrator myself, the trust issue runs both
ways:  you are concerned that you'll be overcharged since the arrangement
isn't direct, but on the other side of the coin, they could well be
worried that they won't be paid for the hours they work!  Best bet:  work
out a contract with them in advance, and stick to it.  If you don't feel
like you're being treated fairly, don't work with them again, and let
others know.

My two cents,

--Sherri

