No, technically it's not programming, but it sure as hell isn't   
typing. 
 
I think html writing should be equated with design work.  There   
are many jobs, from journalism to computer code generating that   
involve data entry but shouldn't be considered on par with typing   
jobs.   
 
The answer is, as it is with most things, whatever the market   
will bear.   
 
The responsiblity of the html writer is to quote on an accurate   
assessment of the work involved.  The responsiblity of the buyer   
is to shop around and discern the difference between good html   
and crap.  Here's a hint... crap is cheaper... but it's crap.     
 
Also the buyer should know what he/she wants.  As a freelancer   
from way back I know that most of the work can often be the   
back-and-forth of tranferring source material, meeting clients,   
clients who change their minds, etc.  These "unbillable hours"   
should be incorperated into the cost of the job.   And the client   
should try not to abuse this position by frequent changes of   
mind, when the job was quoted as a fixed rate. 
 
This is a new trade and in time we'll all learn. 
 
 
